  <!-- Body -->
  <section class="bg-eai-bone">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-16 md:py-20">
      <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-eai-navy/90 leading-relaxed font-serif">

        <p>
          Three risks are worth naming. Each one is a real failure mode, and each one has a
          handling.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Risk 1: Reputational risk on the form.</strong> Some journalists, donors, and
          regulators will read "an AI-run Engine Room" and reach for "hype" before they reach for
          the substance. The structure already lowers this risk relative to anything that puts an
          AI in an officer's chair — no AI holds office here, and a named human is accountable for
          everything. The rest of the handling is two-part. First, plain disclosure — the
          form-statement, /staff, and /substrate pages in Section 3 — so anyone can evaluate the
          form against the operating reality, not a marketing claim. Second, substantive work that
          survives expert scrutiny. The work is the credibility test; the disclosure is the
          integrity test. Done well, the form becomes a feature — a thoughtful <em>Wired</em> story,
          a <em>Stanford Social Innovation Review</em> case. It is one reason the Founding Chair
          wants Tonia leading: her institutional credibility is itself part of the answer to the
          form question.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Risk 2: The operations seam.</strong> Two halves have to stay aligned — the CEO,
          who runs the external and relational work, and the Engine Room, which runs production under
          the Chair. Co-leadership of any kind fails when the lanes are drawn vaguely. The handling:
          the lanes are drawn by document, not by mood — development, donors, board, and public face
          on one side; research, drafting, and the publication line on the other. The Chair directs
          the Engine Room directly; the CEO has dotted-line oversight and the reserved decisions in
          Section 3. If the seam strains, the board convenes and resets it. If it fails, the model
          failed and the Institute restructures — cheaply, because the structure is deliberately
          small.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>Risk 3: Margaret Bird bandwidth.</strong> Margaret has carried the substantive
          scholarship lift for more than a decade and is recovering from the conference she finally
          pulled off. The Institute must not become another demand on her time. Her chair seat is
          extended pending her affirmative consent, and until she gives it she is not in the role.
          Her contributions are episodic and at her pace — occasional briefing reviews, conversations
          with fellows. The recruiting function is instructed not to propose her for operational
          seats, and her name appears on Institute materials only with her affirmative consent on each
          occasion. The scholarship does not rest on her alone; the Institute is built so she can lean
          in when she wants to and stay at arm's length when she needs to, without either choice
          damaging anything.
        </p>

        <hr class="my-12 border-eai-blueprint/30" />

        <p class="italic text-eai-blueprint">
          This is the proposal. The Institute is small enough to be built fast and changed faster; the
          evidence base is real, the moment is now, and the structure is designed so the boldness lives
          in the work, not in the chain of accountability.
        </p>

      </article>
    </div>
